# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: faraday-lectureship-prize
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] The **1904 petition** **to the Chemical Society** was a petition written by 19 female chemists setting out the reasons why they should be afforded the status of Fellow of the Chemical Society.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] The petition is of importance as it eventually led to the admission of women as Fellows of the Society (one of the Societies that amalgamated to become the Royal Society of Chemistry), as well as identifying prominent female chemists working in Britain at this time.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] The Chemical Society was founded in 1841, but several attempts to allow the admission of women as fellows were unsuccessful.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Attempts at change included a legal challenge based on the ambiguous language of the Society’s Charter in 1880, which was defeated because the issue of admitting women as fellows "was not expedient at the present time", followed by an attempt in 1892, defeated by a Council vote of 8 to 7.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] However, after the election of Marie Curie as a Foreign Fellow of the Society in 1904, 19 women signed a petition for admission of women as Fellows.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] The petition was organised by three of its signatories: Ida Smedley, Ida Freund, and Martha Whiteley.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] The petition was addressed to the President and Council of the Chemical Society.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] It highlighted that in the previous thirty years that there were "about 150 women" who had appeared as authors on some 300 papers published by the Society.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] They continue that as the Society deemed it fit to publish the work completed by female chemists, that they should help support this work by enabling "free access to chemical literature and by the right to attend the meetings of the Society".
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] The network that allowed these women to co-sponsor the petition has been examined.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Smedley, Freund, and Whiteley led the petition.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Smedley attended the King Edward VI High School as did Thomas and Hartle.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Freund was a demonstrator and a lecturer at Newnham College, Cambridge between 1887 and 1912, as were Elizabeth Eleanor Field, Dorothy Marshall, and Mildred Gostling.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Thomas, Field, Whiteley, and Gostling spent time at Royal Holloway College, from where there were two additional petitioners: Margaret Seward and Sibyl Widdows.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Clare de Brereton Evans and Millicent Taylor attended the Cheltenham Ladies' College, Cheltenham and Taylor had connections with the University of Bristol, where Emily Fortey and Katherine Williams studied.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Lucy Boole studied at the London School of Medicine for Women and Katherine Burke studied at University College London under the supervision of William Ramsay - both of these women knew de Brereton Evans.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Grace Toynbee studied at the University of Birmingham, and was possibly connected with Hartle.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Two petitioners Edith Humphrey and Alice Smith have unknown connections to the remainder, but it is proposed that they were connected by male chemists keen to promote their cause, such William Ramsay.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] However, when this was put to a vote, only 45 fellows showed up, and the motion was defeated.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] The subsequent discussions led to an eventual compromise in 1908 that women be admissible as "Subscribers" which would allow attendance at ordinary meetings, the use of the library, and the receipt of Society publications.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] Only 11 women joined as "Subscriber" in the period 1908 - 1919, when the category was abolished.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] After World War I, at an extraordinary general meeting on 8 May 1919, the Society under its then President James Dobbie resolved that women should be admitted on the same terms as men, and the corresponding byelaw was passed in 1920.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/1904-petition-to-the-chemical-society] The first woman fellow admitted was Ida Smedley (Mrs Maclean).
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] David Buckingham attended Barker College in Sydney.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He then obtained a Bachelor of Science and Master of Science, under Professor Raymond Le Fevre, from the University of Sydney and a PhD from the University of Cambridge supervised by John Pople.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He was an 1851 Exhibition Senior Student in the Physical Chemistry Laboratory at the University of Oxford from 1955 to 1957, Lecturer and then Student (Fellow) at Christ Church, Oxford from 1955 to 1965 and University Lecturer in the Inorganic Chemistry Laboratory from 1958 to 1965.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He was Professor of Theoretical Chemistry at the University of Bristol from 1965 to 1969.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He was appointed Professor of Chemistry at the University of Cambridge in 1969.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in 1975, a Fellow of the American Physical Society in 1986 and a Foreign Associate of the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1992.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He was a member of the International Academy of Quantum Molecular Science.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] Buckingham was elected to the Australian Academy of Science in 2008 as a Corresponding Fellow.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He was awarded the first Ahmed Zewail Prize in Molecular Sciences for pioneering contributions to the molecular sciences in 2006.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He won the Harrie Massey Medal and Prize in 1995.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He also played 10 first class cricket matches for Cambridge University and Free Foresters between 1955 and 1960, scoring 349 runs including two half-centuries at an average of 18.36.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He was President of Cambridge University Cricket Club between 1990 and 2009.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] Professor Buckingham finished his career as Emeritus Professor of Chemistry at the University of Cambridge, United Kingdom and Emeritus Fellow at Pembroke College, Cambridge.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] Professor Buckingham's research has focussed on the measurement and understanding of the electric, magnetic and optical properties of molecules; as well as on the theory of intermolecular forces.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] Initially he worked on dielectric properties of liquids, such as dipole moments of molecules in both solution and gas phases.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] He developed the theory of the interaction of molecules in liquids and gases with external electric and magnetic fields.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In 1959, he proposed a direct method of measurement of molecular quadrupole moments of molecules (measured in buckinghams), which he demonstrated experimentally in 1963 on the carbon dioxide molecule.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In 1960, he developed theories of solvent effects on nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectra and vibrational spectra of molecules.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In 1962 he considered the effect on NMR spectra of molecular orientation in a strong electric field, and developed a method to determine the absolute sign of the spin-spin coupling constant.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In 1968, he determined the first accurate values of hyperpolarizability using the Kerr effect.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In 1971 Buckingham and Laurence Barron pioneered the study of Raman optical activity, due to differences in the Raman scattering of left and right-polarized light by chiral molecules.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In the 1980s, he showed the importance of long-range intermolecular forces in determining the structure and properties of small molecule clusters, with particular applications in biological macromolecules.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In 1990 he predicted the linear effect of an electric field on the reflection of light at interfaces.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In 1995, he proved that the sum of the rotational strengths of all vibrational transitions from the ground state of a chiral molecule is zero.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] In July 1964, David Buckingham sailed from Southampton to Montréal, to take up a research post in Ottawa.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] On the voyage he met Jillian Bowles, a physiotherapist who was heading to a post in British Columbia.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] They were engaged in January 1965 and married at Christ Church Cathedral, Oxford six months later.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] They were married for over 55 years, and had three children: Lucy Elliot and Mark Vincent, born in Bristol, and Alice Susan born in Cambridge.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] Between them they had eight grandchildren: Carola, Peter, Oliver, William, Patrick, Anna, Samuel and Maeve.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/a-david-buckingham] David Buckingham died in Cambridge on 4 February 2021, seven days after his 91st birthday; he was survived by Jill, their children and grandchildren.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] Carrington was educated at Colfe's School and the University of Southampton where he was awarded the degrees of B.Sc. and Ph.D.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] Carrington was a Fellow of Downing College, Cambridge between 1959 and 1967, where he worked closely with Christopher Longuet-Higgins, and became assistant director of research in 1963.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] In 1967 Carrington returned to the University of Southampton as one of the youngest professors of chemistry in Britain at the time, becoming a Royal Society Research Professor from 1979 until his retirement in 1999.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] Carrington moved his Royal Society Research Professorship from Southampton to the University of Oxford during the period 1984-1987, during which his laboratory was in the (then) Physical Chemistry Laboratories on South Parks Road.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] While at Oxford Carrington was a Fellow of Jesus College, Oxford, Carrington moved his research professorship back to the University of Southampton in 1987, where he remained until his retirement from the University of Southampton in 1999.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] Carrington's earlier contributions to chemical physics were in the fields of electron spin resonance (esr) spectroscopy, and magnetic resonance in general.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] During this period Carrington authored the classic monograph on Magnetic Resonance with Andrew McLachlan, 'Introduction to Magnetic Resonance with Applications to Chemistry and Chemical Physics'.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] Carrington's later work was concerned with examining the structure of molecular ions in energy regions close to their dissociation limits.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] This work on the spectroscopy of simple molecular ions provided accurate measurements with which theoretical calculations could usefully be compared.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] In particular, his work on the simplest diatomic and triatomic molecules gave rise to measurements that have not yet been matched by theoretical calculations.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] Much of this work is reviewed in the classic monograph authored with John M Brown, "Rotational Spectroscopy of Diatomic Molecules".
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] Carrington was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS) in 1971, and received the Faraday Lectureship Prize in 1986 and the Davy Medal in 1992.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] He also became a Foreign Associate of the US National Academy of Sciences in 1994.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] He served as President of the Faraday Division of the Royal Society of Chemistry in 1997-1998.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alan-carrington] He was made a Commander of the Order of the British Empire in 1999 and an Honorary Fellow of Downing College, Cambridge in 2000.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] Pines was born on June 22, 1945, and grew up in Bulawayo in Southern Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe).
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] He studied undergraduate mathematics and chemistry in Israel at Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] Coming to the United States in 1968, Pines obtained his Ph.D. in chemical physics at M.I.T. in 1972 and joined the UC Berkeley faculty later that year.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] Pines died on November 1, 2024, at the age of 79.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] Pines was a pioneer in the development and applications of nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) spectroscopy of non-liquid samples.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] He also developed the areas of multiple-quantum spectroscopy, adiabatic sech/tanh inversion pulses, zero-field NMR, double rotation and dynamic-angle spinning, iterative maps for pulse sequences and quantum control, and the quantum geometric phase.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] His combination of optical pumping and cross-polarization made it possible to observe enhanced NMR of surfaces and the selective "lighting up" of solution NMR and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) by means of laser-polarized xenon.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] Until he retired to emeritus status, his program was composed of two complementary components.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] The first is the establishment of new concepts and techniques in NMR and MRI, in order to extend their applicability and enhance their capability to investigate molecular structure, organization and function from materials to organisms.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] The second component of his research program involves the application of such novel methods to problems in chemistry, materials science, and biomedicine.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] Among his many prestigious awards and honors, Pines received the Langmuir Medal of the American Chemical Society, the Faraday Medal of the Royal Society of Chemistry, the Wolf Prize for Chemistry (together with Richard R.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] Cotton Medal for Excellence in Chemical Research of the American Chemical Society in 1999.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] In 2005, an Ampere Symposium was held in honor of Pines' 60th birthday in Chamonix, France, and in 2008, he was awarded the Russell Varian Prize at the European Magnetic Resonance Conference.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] (Previous Varian Prizes winners: Jean Jeener, Erwin Hahn, Nicolaas Bloembergen, John.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/alexander-pines] Redfield.) Pines was also recognized by numerous teaching honors, including the University of California's Distinguished Teaching Award.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analyst-journal] The journal is abstracted and indexed in MEDLINE and Analytical Abstracts.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analyst-journal] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2022 impact factor of 4.2.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analyst-journal] In 1999, the Royal Society of Chemistry closed the journal *Analytical Communications* because it felt that the material submitted to that journal would be best included in a new communications section of *Analyst*.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analytical-abstracts] Rather than abstracting all articles from a list of analytical journals, *Analytical Abstracts* has a very focussed scope.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analytical-abstracts] Over half a million of articles are selected from a list of over 100 source journals, covering not only analytical chemistry, but also food and environmental chemistry subject areas (amongst others).
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analytical-abstracts] The principal criteria for selecting an article is that it must deal with the practical measurement of one or more chemical species and must involve the use of a novel protocol.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analytical-abstracts] Classification of articles is performed on the basis of three aspects of the article: the analyte, the matrix and the concept.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analytical-abstracts] While it is not necessary for an article to describe all three aspects, at least one of them must be identifiable for inclusion in *Analytical Abstracts*.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analytical-methods-journal] The journal is abstracted and indexed in Chemical Abstracts Service, Science Citation Index, and Scopus.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/analytical-methods-journal] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2021 impact factor of 3.532.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/faraday-lectureship-prize] The **Faraday Lectureship Prize**, previously known simply as the **Faraday Lectureship**, is awarded once every two years (approximately) by the Royal Society of Chemistry for "exceptional contributions to physical or theoretical chemistry".
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/faraday-lectureship-prize] Named after Michael Faraday, the first Faraday Lecture was given in 1869, two years after Faraday's death, by Jean-Baptiste Dumas.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/faraday-lectureship-prize] As of 2009, the prize was worth £5000, with the recipient also receiving a medal and a certificate.
[src:faraday-lectureship-prize/faraday-lectureship-prize] As the name suggests, the recipient also gives a public lecture describing their work.
